<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/blu_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Tournament Reports</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Tournament Reports</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/treports/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/heroclix/treports/treports.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/vs/treports/treports.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/lotr/treports/treports.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/treports/treports.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/blu_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Essen, Germany - October 2004<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11045'>Patrick "Patrick M. S" Sullivan</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11045&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> July 6, 2006</font><p align='justify'><blockquote><font class="bfont"> Note from me: Hey all, I’d been meaning to do this for sometime now. I wanted to move all my Tournament Reports from the Decipher and DGMA sites to Decktech and Gameplayersnetwork since they are easier to find here and I’m worried that Decipher’s two sites will go down eventually. I wouldn’t want to lose all these awesome memories. So here they are, archived, for your amusement. Feel free to give reviews with your thoughts and memories of the events or to simply let me know how you liked the read. <br />
<br />
Mr. Sullivan goes to Germany<br />
<br />
Pre-tourney Jank <br />
Well, I can’t believe that I’m actually going to this event after all. I’ve heard about it for two years in a row on how it is THE event to attend for LOTR both in terms of competition and in terms of fun. I remember how many times I said there was almost a zero percent chance of me going this year, but in the end, I ended up qualifying with a team I put together at Worlds this year and that tips the scales just enough to make me want to go. <br />
At worlds, as you may recall, I qualified in a team tournament playing with Kenneth Ellingsen from Norway and Michel Alain from Quebec. Michel couldn’t make the trip to World Cup so I was allowed to replace him with someone else (you only need two of the original qualifying team to use the bye into Day Two). So, as some of you remember, I put out requests on various websites looking for someone who was bold enough to join our team. Kenneth and I received a couple dozen applications and we decided to go with Martin Hechtberger from Austria. Martin has been doing exceptionally well this year, winning two Online PSQs and one of the two Online PSIs (winning more than 1,000$ so far). Martin makes an exceptional team member to our already gifted team and we’re happy to have him. <br />
Both Kenneth and I have been doing very well this year as well so I really think that our team stands a decent chance at winning this whole event. This will be my first World Cup so I’ll be anxious to see how differently it plays out in terms of strategic pairings and timed matches being a problem or not. <br />
I’m not sure what Martin is bringing with him at this point. I know that Kenneth is bringing a Dauntless Hunter fellowship with Enduring Nazgul corruption shadow that he claims is close to unbeatable. I’ll take his word for it and trust him completely so I’m not too worried there. <br />
As for me, I decided on two decks that I will interchange as I see fit between days. My primary deck is Ninja Elves which is basically an all-elf fellowship with Frodo Ring-bearer paired with a Ninja Gollum shadow that Kenneth keeps telling me to throw a 4th Shelob into (which I stupidly continue to ignore). It’s the deck I’ve been playing a lot online lately and have great faith in its ability to turn unfavourable match-ups into winning scenarios. I threw in a second copy of Radagast since he seems to be winning me more games than I can remember. <br />
My second deck is an elf-man classic fellowship built by Toronto’s own Mike Ium, paired with Beseigers. I find this shadow really delivers the mail most of the time even in unfavourable match-ups. Those trolls are sick. <br />
So with these decks and capable teammates, I believe we stand a good chance at placing highly, if not winning the whole event. It’s going to be a grueling 4-days of tournament-play (since we get a bye into Day Two, we save ourselves from the running the Day One gauntlet). <br />
So without further ado, I pack my backs, write up deck lists, and begin my voyage to World Cup 2004’ <br />
Day Zero<br />
Tuesday, October 19th, 2004<br />
Hey Matthew Broderick, I want my 2 hours back <br />
So, I wake up sick as a dog which just sucks since I know there will be no chance of getting better in Essen what with all the lack of sleep, drinking, etc. So, I manage to get half a work day in and then go home to nap until 8pm when I got to get to the airport. I set like 12 different alarm clocks since I’m terrified of missing my flight. All the alarm clocks end up going off at once and I almost have a heart attack right then and there. <br />
So, I’m off and away to the Montreal airport where I grab a couple scotches to help me sleep on the plane and then hop on the plane. Luckily we leave on time so I don’t have to worry about missing my connecting flight out of London. On the way, I have to watch The Stepford Wives which is like this terrible movie with Nicole Kidman and Matthew Broderick. I’m actually really excited to watch On The Waterfront, but I fall asleep and miss the whole thing. <br />
Day One<br />
Wednesday, October 20th, 2004<br />
16 bucks is too much for ordinary scotch <br />
The connecting flight is uneventful and I land in Dusseldorf airport around 2 or 3 in the afternoon on Wednesday. The stress level goes up immediately as most of the signs are written in German and I have to figure out how the heck to get to the train station and then to Essen. I used to think I’d be pretty good at that Amazing Race reality TV Show but now, I’m not so sure. I end up figuring out the train thing and hop on, realizing as soon as the train takes off that I have no way of knowing how long the train ride is to Essen or when I get off. <br />
Luckily Essen’s main train station (Essen HBF) is clearly indicated so I don’t get off at the wrong stop. Now the tricky part, trying to find my hotel. I start asking around and everyone is pointing me in a different direction on how to get to the Sheraton. I end up walking around for almost two hours running through parks filled with wet leaves (keep in mind, I have ALL my luggage) and other wonderful spots in Essen trying to find the blasted hotel. I finally do and the hotel receptionist doesn’t seem to have a key set aside for me. I start the process of raising my voice saying how I’ve been walking around for hours and I need to sleep and she quickly gives me a key. So I fall asleep in no time and get woken up a little later when the Decipher and DGMA crews get back from Day One World Cup. <br />
I grab a spaghetti Bolognese in the bar downstairs and a REALLY overpriced scotch. I keep forgetting how expensive scotch is to drink in Germany and Austria so I better stick with wine and coke for the rest of the trip. I’m having dinner with Trevor, Kyle, Enrique, Girard and a couple others at this point. Enrique and Tristan decide to introduce me to the wonderful world of Mango Ice Cream so I order a couple scoops and I’ll be damned if it isn’t the best ice cream I’ve ever had in my entire life. I’m a big Ben & Jerry’s fan too, but this is even better than their Chunky Monkey. So, off to bed with me crazy worried about tomorrow’s Day Two. I hear that the Greeks that won Day One World Cup have some sort of new meta which is incredible. I’m really looking forward to seeing it. <br />
Day Two<br />
Thursday, October 21st, 2004<br />
Doubling to site 5 is tough <br />
So, I get up around 7 or so (which is like 1 in the morning Montreal-time), have like the BEST water-pressure shower ever and then hit the big breakfast buffet downstairs which comes with the room. There, Toonces from Worlds Apart (company behind LOTR Online) is sitting at a table by himself but I decide to leave him be and sit with the Decipher and DGMA crew. I have some of the most orange scrambled eggs I’ve ever seen, some bacon, awful sausages and a few other delectable treats (crazy good coffee and orange juice though). And we’re off to the convention hall by subway. <br />
Getting there, all the Decipher guys are allowed to enter at 9am but I have to wait until 10am since I don’t have a badge yet. The line is crazy long but still nothing compared to ComicCon, Origins or GenCon lines. Also, the price is SO much better. For a four-day pass, it was only 22 Euro which is like 25$ or so. In the past, I’ve paid 80$ for a 3-day badge at the American conventions. I’m still too early, though, since it’s only 9h30 so I have a cappuccino which is KILLER good and wait until the flood gates open to the main halls. <br />
Once they do, the size of this convention astounds me. It’s easily the biggest convention I’ve ever seen. There are like 10-12 different MASSIVE halls of exhibits and the Decipher section is in the farthest one. So I make my way through a labyrinth of exhibits, games (including a LIVE-ACTION fuse-ball table where players are strapped into these giants bars that move side to side trying to kick the soccer ball. <br />
I find the Decipher booth and it’s the biggest one I’ve seen yet. There are a ton of tables for demos, a TV showing a WARS promotional slideshow, 3 different booths to buy stuff, a meeting room and 8 computers set up to demo LOTR Online. Each computer gives you a full playset too, so I jump on that and build a few decks to waste some time. There are a ton of tables set up in the back for World Cup and I run into my teammate Martin soon thereafter. Luckily he fits in my XXL Team KwyjiboKardz t-shirt so we’re off to the races. We see that we’re paired up against Hungary right away and I tell him I’m playing Ninja Elves to which he’s not too impressed. I then tell him that my B deck is man-elf/Besieger which he seems to hate even more so I stick with ninja Gollum with Elves and hope for the best. Kenneth ends up being an hour late, but the World Cup doesn’t start on time so for 60 minutes I’m having a heart attack trying to decide if I can get another teammate like Benoit Lemaire or someone equally good. Jonas Skali ends up breaking his hand and doesn’t show up so his team gets a last-minute replacement too. <br />
Anyway, we’re in the bottom-half of the World Cup bracket (6th seeded team out of 15) so I’m really happy that we won’t have to see Team Greece, Elf, Dwarf and a few other huge teams until the finals. In our bracket, we have two sanctuary teams that worry me slightly (Team Gollum and Team Rohan). So at around 11h30 or so, the World Cup starts. We get to play Team Hungary first and I can’t remember who gets first pairing. I have no idea what these guys are playing so we pretty much just randomly pick pairings. <br />
Now in these events, in case you don’t know, each player plays a best-of-three match-up of 45-minute timed rounds. If two of the three players of a team win their match-ups, that team advances. The losing team goes to the loser bracket and tries to win the rest of their matches. Any team that loses twice is eliminated from the World Cup. The trick is to try and not lose for as long as possible since the sooner you move into the loser’s bracket, you have to win TWICE as many games as you do trying to advance through that bracket compared to the winner’s bracket. So, losing to Team Hungary would make winning the World Cup a very unlikely event for our team, Team Gondor (I tried everything I could to get our team to keep the traditional Team KwyjiboKardz but nothing could be done). Many people (namely Worlds Apart staff) were calling our team, Team Online, since all three of us are prominent LOTR Online players. <br />
Anyway, on to our first match: <br />
Preliminary Round One<br />
Team Gondor vs Team Hungary<br />
Game One<br />
Opponent: Daniel Holtiger<br />
Deck: Noble Leaders - Besiegers<br />
Good: This is a good match-up for my deck<br />
Bad: He forgets to use Rohirrim Road against me<br />
Ugly: At site 5, my Enquea kills a companion blowing up 5 threats which kills him<br />
Result: FW Shadow Kill site 5<br />
1-0 <br />
Martin wins his match and Kenneth loses to Gabor Vida (who is playing a lot faster this year than last year) <br />
Game Two<br />
Opponent: same<br />
Deck: same<br />
Good: I bid 4 to his 0<br />
Bad: I played too aggressively and moved too fast<br />
Ugly: I double into 5 with 4 companions and get slammed<br />
Result: FL shadow kill site 5<br />
1-1<br />
Both Martin and Ken lose their second games so Kenneth has lost his match-up which means BOTH Martin and I have to win our 3rd games. I’m sure I can and he’s sure he can as well. <br />
Game Three<br />
Opponent: same<br />
Deck: same<br />
Good: This was the toughest match of the three which is fitting for 3rd game<br />
Bad: I double into 5 again versus besiegers. A big no-no I’m beginning to think<br />
Ugly: The double into 5 ends up being really good. <br />
Result: FW site 9<br />
2-1 <br />
So, I win my match-up and so does Marty so, we throw team Hungary into the losers’ bracket and move on to face our first sanctuary team, Team Gollum headed by France’s Benoit Lemaire. <br />
They are a higher-seeded team so they get to make first match-up. They pair up Matz Kathage (excellent German player) against me while Marty and Ken take the other two. <br />
Preliminary Round Two<br />
Game One<br />
Opponent: Matz Kathage<br />
Deck: Southron Archery / Rainbow madness<br />
Good: He was one cool player with one VERY cool fellowship<br />
Bad: I doubled to five and it didn’t work out at ALL this time<br />
Ugly: I’m down to Frodo and Cirdan for the rest of the site path who succumb at site 8<br />
Result: FL shadow kill site 8<br />
0-1<br />
I think that both Kenneth and Martin lost their first matches too so it looks like Team Gollum is going to be giving us much more trouble than we anticipated. <br />
Game Two<br />
Good: I played this game better with a key double to site 5 when he had a bad hand. <br />
Bad: I’m at site 8 and he’s at site 6 and I played a bunch of cards for NO REASON. I should NOT have given him phases to play his maneuver events and such. He had a bunch of slaked thirsts and quick as may be in his hand. <br />
Ugly: I do play a bunch of minions at site 6 however and Frodo is forced to put on the ring to help take threat wounds from Enquea. He goes up to nine burdens. Smeagol then adds two threats to assign Gollum or something and I end up killing another companion in the fierce skirmishes. Matz carelessly drops a threat wound on Frodo since he has a bunch of vitality remaining and I remind him that he’s currently wearing the ring thus corrupting Frodo and losing the game by accident. Oops. <br />
Result: FW corruption win site 6<br />
1-1 <br />
Kenneth wins his match and Martin loses his. So both Kenneth AND myself have to win our third games. So much pressure and it’s only day two of World Cup! <br />
Game Three<br />
Good: I have him up to 6 burdens by site 2<br />
Bad: This game finished very quick. <br />
Ugly: He carelessly (again) assigns Frodo to Gollum. Frodo has 3 vitality remaining and is NOT wearing the green ring. I have 6 cards in hand and Matz forgot that They Stole It wounds Frodo twice, not once. So, I wound Frodo 4 times and win the game. <br />
Result: FW Shadow Kill, site THREE<br />
2-1<br />
Kenneth manages to win his game as well and we stay undefeated and make it to tomorrow’s Semi-Final match-up against Team Rohan (another sanctuary team). <br />
It was great playing Matz, he was an excellent opponent with a great sense of humour who smiled and laughed as much in our games as I did. I hope to see more players like him in my future match-ups. <br />
So, Marty retires early while Kenneth and I grab his Norwegian friend Howard. Howard has been eliminated from the World Cup as Team Norway and must be frustrated as he kept winning his match-ups while both his teammates only lost their match-ups. So we go to the local pizza joint and I grab a nice plate of gnocci while Kenneth tries the proscuito pizza. <br />
We discuss meta choices for the next day and while Marty is going to probably change his deck, Kenneth decides to stick with his Dauntless Hunter / Enduring Nazgul corruption beatdown deck while I elect to stay with my Ninja elves. <br />
So I head back to the Sheraton and stay up late with Scott Martins from Worlds Apart and a few others while enjoying a bunch of ice-cream from the hotel (I’m now trying the Bourbon Vanilla along with the mango). <br />
Day Three<br />
Friday, October 22nd, 2004 <br />
Margaritas with Sansiba <br />
So again a huge breakfast and I’m off to face off Team Rohan made up of the top-placing Greeks from Day One Worlds. <br />
I meet up with Kenneth and Marty and we won’t have first pick of pairings so we sort of wish we were playing the same decks or something. Still we aren’t overly concerned, but these Greek guys are a helluvah a lot more intimidating looking than our previous opponents (read: Benowitt LeMary). One of these guys (I’m gonna take a wild guess and say that his name is George) pairs himself against Marty and this dude has like the coolest hair I’ve ever seen. It’s beaded and goes beyond this guy’s waist. Pretty wicked. The dude that is paired against Kenneth (which ends up being the worst possible match-up for Ken) has piercings in and around his face. Finally my guy, Asimdkid (sp’) looks like a cross between a pro wrestler and the Castamir of Umbar (non-foil). <br />
**Quarter-Finals**<br />
Game One<br />
Opponent: Asimdkid Mariopoulos<br />
Deck: Knight-Gandalf / Morcs<br />
Good: Man, this was a TOUGH match for me<br />
Bad: He accidentally kills Gandalf by making Gollum strength +3 in the Fierce skirmish without realizing that the +3 boost is until the regroup phase. So Gollum is 11 strength and I play We Must Have It to send the Leader of Men into the Shadow. Yay for me! Condition removers are BAD for Ninja Gollum so I’m glad to see him go. <br />
Ugly: He forgets that site 7 reduces the move limit while I have Radagast at site 6 and I triple for the win! (LOL) <br />
Result: FW site 9<br />
1-0<br />
Kenneth gets mauled in his match and isn’t even close to being able to beat that deck, while Martin gets into a real ugly timed win situation where his opponent is accusing Marty of stalling. Not pretty and I’m glad I am not playing that guy. <br />
Game Two<br />
Opponent: Same dude whose name makes KwyjiboKardz look like John Smith<br />
Deck: Same<br />
Good: He doesn’t get his Deep in Thought all game which is HUGE for me<br />
Bad: I had to double to 5 and then double against to 7<br />
Ugly: Ouf.. Site 7, he plays a MASSIVE squad using Osgiliath Crossing to completely destroy me. <br />
Result: FL Shadow Kill site 7<br />
1-1<br />
Marty loses his second match in a timed loss to the guy that accused Marty of stalling. So I see that timed games are a serious issue for these two players. When the stakes are this high, players don’t rush through phases and by giving players FULL wins for timed wins, clearly this situation is going to happen. Anyway, Kenneth loses his second match and ONCE AGAIN, it’s up to Marty and me to BOTH win our third games. I hate these situations. But this is what the World Cup is all about. <br />
Game Three<br />
Opponent: Same dude who smokes the NASTIEST cigarettes I’ve ever smelled. <br />
Deck: Same brutal build<br />
Good: He decides to double into site 3 and I get the most BEAUTIFUL reconcile I have EVER drawn. Captured By the Ring, Promise Keeping, Shelob, They Stole It. THANK YOU. <br />
Bad: Time was a problem since he used 15 minutes to decide how to deal with site 3. <br />
Ugly: Gandalf died early but he plays Sent Back to play Gandalf again and THEN plays Deep in Thought the same turn! Just when I thought this problem was over! <br />
Result: Timed Win site 6<br />
2-1<br />
Martin gets another TIMED WIN and we barely defeat these guys. We thought we were done for after Kenneth was eliminated but we managed to squeak out a win to win a spot in the Semi-finals against the only other undefeated team, Team Elf made up of the best German players I’ve ever seen. <br />
**Semi Finals**<br />
Game One<br />
Opponent: Dennis Schmitz<br />
Deck:Elf/Corsairs! <br />
Good: This is a terrific match-up! I eat corsairs for breakfast with Galadriel, Legolas, Cirdan and Gil-Galad<br />
Bad: I must be out of my mind. I decide to make possessions and conditions cost +8 using my Rohirrm Road and then I TRIPLE to site 4! I know Corsairs need to set up so I figure I’ll give him a hard time. <br />
Ugly: I keep losing companions like crazy (those corsairs are tough) but Tale of the Great Ring wins me the game. <br />
Result: FW site 9<br />
1-0<br />
Kenneth wins his match but Martin loses his and doesn’t think he’ll be able to win his match-up. <br />
Game Two<br />
Opponent: Bucket-cap versus Bucket-cap (I’m wearing my Olympic Canadian bucket hat and Dennis is also sporting a handsome bucket-cap) <br />
Deck: Same good match up. How can I lose’ <br />
Good: He doubles to site 3 and loses Galadriel against my condition and possession heavy-shadow! <br />
Bad: I lose a bunch of guys at site 2 due to a Castamir with Halberd wand Red Wrath. <br />
Ugly: Frodo and Galadriel are left trying to make it to site 6 with no Gil-Galad allowed to be played since I can’t spot 2 elf companions. <br />
Result: FL shadow kill site 5<br />
1-1<br />
Kenneth wins his match but Marty loses his! So you know what that means’!’! It’s all up to ME in the third game. I HAVE to win my third match to make it into the finals! Pressure much’ Good thing is that this is a very good match up so I should be ok. <br />
Game Three<br />
Opponent: Dennis Schmitz<br />
Deck: Corsairs-Elf<br />
Good: Nothing. I got really distracted in this game and had EVERY intention of bidding 3 or 4 since I know he can’t bid higher. But then I see him reach under the table during the bidding process and bring his hand back up in a split second. Everytime I’ve seen a player do this, they end up bidding zero since they obviously didn’t count any tokens. So I decide to bid 1 instead so that I can avoid getting into trouble at the Halls of the Dead (or whatever that site 4 that gets Castamir is). <br />
Bad: He bids TWO! OH NO! Now, not only do I NOT get my Rohirrm Road but it gives him extra time to reconcile into a killer site two hand against me! <br />
Ugly: Castamir hits the table at site 2 with Red Wrath and I lose Cirdan and Glorfindel. After that, I just couldn’t stop losing companions. <br />
Result: FL shadow kill site 8<br />
1-2<br />
OH NO! I let down my team! This is my biggest nightmare situation. I am the reason we lose a match-up. So we get bumped down to the loser’s bracket. The good news is that this is pretty much the longest you can wait to get knocked down to that bracket so we only have to win ONE match-up to get back into the finals against Team Elf. <br />
We have to play tomorrow morning’s winner of Team Gollum versus Team Rohan. We REALLY don’t want to play those Greek guys again cuz we think we can handle Benoit’s Team Gollum much easier. So, Kenneth and I decide to keep our same decks while Marty switches his deck up again. <br />
That night, Decipher and DGMA staff have to attend a distributor dinner at some Greek restaurant. I hate Greek food like poison so I’m happy to skip out. Head judge Enrique Huerta is up for returning to Dolores’ Mexican restaurant that he remembers from last year. So, we grab some directions from the hotel staff and walk all the way to the restaurant. Upon arrival, we see that Tristan, his girlfriend Miranda, Head Judge Eric Minkes and a ton of other dAgent volunteers are gathered at a big table. So we join them and notice in very little time that Margaritas are 2 for 1. <br />
So, I’m almost sound asleep from exhaustion and jet-lag, but a few drinks later I’m laughing up a storm and taking Enrique’s dares to ask my waitress her name. She is SO beautiful and she tells me her name is Sanseeba. So, we go through the lime, strawberry and peach varieties of the Mexican drink and settle on the Strawberry flavoured one in no time. Seven drinks later, I’m feeling pretty good but it’s not strong enough to make my terrible Meat and Chicken plate taste any good. Oh well. We start the long walk back to the hotel, singing the whole way and acting like idiots. <br />
When we arrive, the Decipher crew is back in the lobby having drinks and snacks, and guess what’ Time for Mango ice cream! At this point, I’m feeling pretty sick and decide to retire to bed around 2 in the morning. <br />
Day Four <br />
Saturday, October 23rd, 2004<br />
OLAY! <br />
So, the wake-up call comes in at like 7h30 or so and Trevor is too tired to respond properly into the telephone so he grunts into it and hangs up. Five minutes later, a German woman barges into our room to wake us up. Apparently, the wake-up lady takes her job very seriously. <br />
Anyway, I’m far too hung-over to get up with the rest of the Decipher staff and have a nice breakfast with them. So, I ask Trevor to get the wake-up call for me moved to 9am while he goes and sets up the booth and tournament and stuff. So at 9am, she calls back and I tell her to call back in a hour. At 10am, she calls back and I hang up the phone and set the TV alarm for 10h30. When that finally goes off, I realize my teammates are probably a little pissed off at me since I said to meet me at 10 in the morning and I won’t be able to get there for at least an hour. <br />
So I slowly wake up, shower, have a late breakfast and head over to the convention centre at like 11h30 or so. My teammates are nowhere to be found, but I run into Team Rohan on the subway who are obviously very late for their match-up versus team Gollum. We arrive at the same time and everyone tells me Ken and Marty are mad at me. Uh oh. <br />
Anyway, Eric tells me that I can’t look at the game since I’ll be playing the winners and then Benoit comes up to me and tells me the same thing. To him, I respond that I’ll be sending a team of professional scouters to watch the game for me and report everything back. It’s not true of course but I figure it’ll get a rise out of my favourite Frenchman. Which it did, of course. He proceeds to call me a cheater and stuff and I bask in the glory of my successful puppet-mastery. <br />
Luckily for my team, Benoit’s Team Gollum wins and proceeds to play us. They are top-seeded so they get first pairing. They pair Matz versus Kenneth which is an insanely bad match-up for Kenneth since Matz plays Don’t Look at Them, Preparations, Slaked Thirsts, Quick as may Be and Archery. Enduring Nazzies don’t get along with much of that. <br />
It’s now our turn to pair up and I choose Benoit since I assume he’s playing Dworcs. (that’s Dwarves with morcs). He says, ‘merci.’ Which means thank you in French in that he’s pleased with my choice of picking him. So I figure I must be screwed. <br />
**Semi Finals**<br />
Game One<br />
Opponent: France’s top ranking, Benoit Lemaire<br />
Deck: Dworcs<br />
Good: This was a great match<br />
Bad: I misplay and at site 6, he could have killed me if he saw how to. <br />
Ugly: I have to triple to try and win to 9 and I majorly misplay site 9 and end up losing all my companions which I could have perhaps kept alive. <br />
Result: FL shadow kill site 9<br />
Both Martin and Kenneth win their matches thankfully so I don’t feel as bad for screwing up. I lost my last match-up yesterday so I really don’t want to let down the team so I rethink how to beat this deck. Benoit successfully got into my head at the beginning by accusing me of netdecking and not being original at World Cup. I thought that was rather ridiculous and was about to explain to him what playing for money entails when Marty pipes in and tells Benoit that Marty’s deck is stolen from Benoit’s online build that he uses for LOTR Online. This bothers Benoit to no end and I’m crazy impressed with Marty for getting inside the Frenchman’s head. Now, if I can only get him to surrender’ <br />
Game Two<br />
Opponent: Benoit again<br />
Deck: Same thing<br />
Good: I had a MUCH better start this time by punishing Benoit at site 3 and my fellowship got a free double to 3. <br />
Bad: I don’t draw into any of my three Promise Keepings until site 8<br />
Ugly: I have to try and double to nine again to try and win. <br />
Result: FL shadow kill site 9<br />
0-2<br />
Ah nuts! I’ve lost my last two match-ups. I know that Dalton is probably trolling the message boards at this point calling me the anchor of my team or something (and rightfully so). Meanwhile Marty wins his match-up while Kenneth loses! <br />
So now Kenneth has to win his third game in order for us to make it into the finals instead of being eliminated from the World Cup. This seems almost impossible in that Kenneth’s match up for his Enduring Nazgul is beyond terrible. So Marty and I tell Ken to bid very high and double EVERY site to try and win against Matz’s southern Archery. Ken agrees and tries this approach. Marty and I watched the whole game and it was a real nail-biter. Kenneth was moving through Matz’s shadow without any problems while Matz’s fellowship was doing the same through Ken. Luckily Ken had the lead and makes it to site 9 for the win! <br />
So, our team has made it to the finals! This is fantastic because otherwise we would have only won 300$ each but the prize support for 1st or 2nd is 5 times that amount. So this was the biggest win ever and the team is ecstatic. We start to discuss what decks to play versus Team Elf the next day and Kenneth decides to keep the same (this ends up being a terrible mistake) while Marty decides to play Knights with morcs and I have to think about mine. I know I don’t want to play Ninja Elves ever again. Marty agrees. So I offer to bring in my killer Elf-man/Besieger deck that Mike Ium built for me and Josh. Marty thinks that deck is even worse so I can’t play that either. He offers to rebuild my Worlds deck (Noble Leaders) but with a Beasterling shadow that should kill elves. I agree that this is an excellent idea and we decide to meet the morning at 10am to make final meta choices. <br />
So, now it’s time for celebration. Many better and wiser players would take this time to playtest but hey, when’s the next time I’ll be in Germany’ So, Enrique and I convince the entire Decipher and DGMA staff to try the Mexican place, since the Margaritas are 2 for 1 Saturday night as well! The place is called Dolores’ Cantina and that is all Toonces’ needs to start playing the Cantina music from Star Wars. I’m immediately happy that the Worlds Apart staff joined us as well. So we take the subway this time over and arrive and the place is PACKED. However, we have the secret weapon known as Marcus Sheppard with his 18 charisma and he manages to reserve a long table for us while we wait at the bar for 40 minutes or so. So, I sit in the middle of the bar with Kyle Heuer (that’s pronounced Hoy-yer, like Lawyer), Toonces and Scott Martins. We get the margaritas flowing immediately and Scott orders some TERRIBLE guacamole but decent meatballs, nachos and wings. However, the best part is that right in front of us is this GIANT ice-chucker used to crush ice for the purposes of making margaritas, pina coladas, you name it. This ice-chucker has this giant handle on it and gets pushed down every time ice cubes are placed inside it to shove them down into the grinder. Anyway, it quickly is decided that this machine is the best invention since sliced bread and the four of us grow a deep respect for the power of the ice-chucker. <br />
That is, until Scott decides that we should cheer the machine every time it is brought into operation. So, it is decided that every time the busboy comes along to make his ice, we shall shout OLAY! Every time the handle is pressed down, that is. Please note that OLAY should be written OLE with a little cute accent on the E but I can’t figure out where the accent button is on my computer so I’m writing it out as OLAY so you know what I mean. Anyway, in no time at all, the young busboy arrives with his bucket of ice and starts to put ice into the machine, Toonces, Scott, Kyle and myself exchange glances and as soon as the handle is pressed down, the four of us shout OLAY! Right in the guy’s ear! We are like 2 feet MAX from the busboy and the four of us start screaming OLAY over and over and over every time he presses the handle down. The guy has a good reaction to it though, and has this big goofy smile like he thinks he’s our hero or something just cuz he’s making ice. Anyway, it was really fun. <br />
So, we grab a table JUST on the other side of the bar and for the rest of the evening, every time I’m talking to Kyle and we start to hear the machine roar into operation, Kyle drops his utensils on his plate, jumps up on his chair, looks around the corner to see and starts shouting OLAY! Over and over and over again. I don’t know if this sounds funny or just crazy, but it was SO HILARIOUS after 8 or 9 margaritas. It was enough of a special occasion that Kyle Heuer’s online name will probably be changed to the icechuck-inator or something. <br />
I should probably mention that Sansiba (remember her’) was also working that night and she walks over to Kevin Reitzel (who also finds her very attractive) and he decides to ask her name. She then tells him that her name is Pepe. I’m all like WHAT’! I’ve been bamboozeled! She’s giving us fake names. Turns out her real name is Irena but I could care less at this point. <br />
The food FINALLY arrives and I ordered tacos. They decided to cover my tacos with salad and LOTS of salad dressing. It was SO GROSS. I guess that’s what I get for ordering tacos a million light years away from the Mexican border. <br />
So, we leave the establishment and begin the long drunk walk back to the hotel where we settle in for some cokes and ice cream. Luckily, Enrique has a bunch of dice on him so it’s time for America’s favourite game, Liar’s Dice! So Enrique, Toonces, Kyle, Tristan, myself and one or two others start a couple games in which Enrique and Kyle reign supreme. However, the term, ‘tooncinated’ is born for whenever you call a bluff and get cheesed. <br />
Enough madness for one evening, time for bed. <br />
Day Five<br />
Sunday, October 24th, 2004<br />
For Vienna Martin! <br />
So, I wake up at 8 or so, try to take a shower without singing that stupid Cantina music that’s been stuck in my head cuz of Toonces, and go grab some breakfast. <br />
I arrive early at the convention hall and grab another amazing cappuccino to get my mind where I need it to be. I hook up with Martin and Ken and get my deck. I should spend more time reviewing it since I completely forget what Aragorn’s beginning of fellowship phase gametext does (exert one companion to heal another of another culture). <br />
We quickly realize that we should have all played the exact same deck today since if we manage to beat Team Elf in the first match-up, they get to readjust pairings for the second-match-ups. This is a ridiculous advantage for their team that can ONLY be negated by playing the same deck. But we don’t have a lot of experience playing in a World Cup so we don’t realize this until it’s too late. Still, we are beyond happiness and satisfaction for making it this far so we’ll just do the best we can do. <br />
Team Elf is made up of some of the finest German players there are. Simon Schebben is the team captain and although he looks exactly like Napoleon Dyanmite’s older brother, Kip (braces and all), he is a gentlemen with a great sense of humour and a great player. Dennis Schmitz (the dude with the bucket hat who also smiles all the time, which is cool) is still alive and kicking and they have some really young player, Bernd, or something who seems to always be in a bad mood or something. <br />
So, they have top seeding so they pair Dennis against Kenneth’s Dauntless Enduring Naz. It is once again, a very mad shadow match-up for Ken’s enduring Nazgul but his fellowship should be able to kill Dennis’ beasterling build without any problems. Assuming of course that Ken gets the draws. <br />
We get second pairing and I put myself for a team captain versus Team Captain duel, Simon Schebben. Meanwhile, Marty’s Knights with Morcs is playing against Bernd’s beasterlings with elves. That’s a pretty fair match-up. <br />
As for me, my Noble-leaders with Beasterlings are playing against elves with Morcs. This is a very similar match-up that I had at Day Three Worlds this year against Bryce Stevensen. This is ordinarily a good match-up for me assuming I get the Curse Their Foul Feet when I need them and don’t get too draw-screwed on my combo-intensive Beasterlings. <br />
I think it’s possible that we can win this match-up especially with Kenneth and myself having very good match-ups. Let’s see what happens: <br />
**World Cup 2004 Finals**<br />
Game One<br />
Opponent: Simon Schebben<br />
Deck: Elves with Smeagol tech - Morcs<br />
Good: Very good match-up for me<br />
Bad: Nothing. Great game. <br />
Ugly: I pull off a beautiful triple to site 6 that sets up perfectly up for single-moving to site 7, 8 and 9 afterwords. <br />
Result: FW site 9<br />
1-0<br />
Ken loses and Marty loses as well I think. Doesn’t look good. Ken says he can win his match-up but Marty doesn’t think he can win his own match-up. <br />
Game Two<br />
Good: I bid one, thinking he’ll bid zero since he starts Smeagol and will never want to go to 2 burdens against my deck early. However, he ends up bidding two bringing him to three burdens! <br />
Bad: In the last 12 cards of my deck, there were 3 Legolas, Greenleaf present which are ESSENTIAL against Morcs. <br />
Ugly: He lets me assign a big Gollum at one point and I kill Sam instead of Smeagol. That was a huge mistake on my part. <br />
Result: FL site 9<br />
1-1<br />
Ken loses his second game and is out while Marty wins! So once again, both Marty and I have to win our third games to stay alive. <br />
Game Three<br />
Good: This time I bid 3 to his 2 and win going first which is really important. <br />
Bad: I don’t draw into ANY polearms this game. <br />
Ugly: He has no choice but to double to 7 and I know he will so I set him up for the beating of his life. <br />
Result: FW site 9 with Elrond, Herald to Gil-Galad who comes up to fight with my Swan-ship tech! 2-1! <br />
Now Marty’s game is still going. And all Team Gondor’s hopes are on Marty. He has no choice but to double to site 9 and wins up facing against 4 fierce big guys (including a Castamir) with his 4 member fellowship including Isildur. Bernd has a discovered which he uses to great damage against the Stone Tower and it’s all over for Marty and our team. <br />
Still, second place is excellent and I’m very pleased with winning 600$US cash and 1,000 decipher dollars which I will hopefully use for travel vouchers in the coming year to get me to Vegas and all sorts of fun places like that. <br />
Now at this point, I’m not sure what to do with myself so I notice a really cute girl playing LOTR Online on one of the demo computers. I also see that there is a free seat next to her. So I go and take it and notice that she’s playing against an online user, Simon, who is my friend in Montreal. So I say, ‘hey! You’re playing a friend of mine!’ to which she responds, ‘cool, can you help me’ I don’t know how to play this deck very well.’ So I’m like, ‘sure’ and sit next to her, log into that terminal and click on her game lobby so that I can observe the game and send messages to Simon. Now this is a german girl, I think, who is speaking English to me so I figure I’m safe sending French messages to Simon. So I write him (in French), ‘hey Simon, it’s Patrick. Guess who you’re playing against’’ To which he responds, ‘Hi Patrick. I give up. Who am I playing against’’ <br />
Now remember, we’re writing each other in French while I’m vocally giving her tricks on how to use her Enduring Nazgul more effectively. So, then I write Simon in French, ‘you’re playing against this GORGEOUS girl. In fact, I just can’t believe how cute she is.’ At this point, she looks over at my screen, reads what I just wrote and says, ‘merci.’ Which of course means thank you in French. So, then I continue writing Simon (cuz I have to fill him in on the humiliating blunder I just made), ‘OMG, she speaks French. I’m turning as red as that stupid Sauron orc you just played.’ To which she cracks up and I leave cuz I’m so embarrassed. Great way to meet a girl though, I guess. <br />
So, Eric Minkes is starting up a Reflections Booster Draft, so I figure what the heck. I pay the 15 Euro and buy 4 Reflections boosters to draft. I end up drafting not one but TWO Sauron, Lord of the Rings! I also draft a French Balrog, Flame of Udun and 2 Galadriel ring-bearers. So I draft her ring and Elrond, Lord of Rivendell along with 2 Vilyas. So, I should be able to use Vilya to put either a Balrog or Sauron on top of my draw deck and have Galadriel overwhelm big minions, yes’ I also draft an elite rider with horse and Uri with a Ring of Fury. Luckily with all these rings, I brought my Binding Ring to start with Galadriel. Unfortunately she only has 4 resistance since I have NO other elf companions so I can only snag one ring. <br />
Anyway, three rounds with 10 players or so. Kenneth Ellingsen is also playing and he drafts, Durin III, Uri and ALL the rings (except the Ring of Fury), so he’s looking pretty strong for the win. <br />
Game One<br />
Opponent: dAgent of the year, Tristan’s Girlfriend, Miranda. Oh great, my DGMA boss is sitting beside me while I try and beat his girlfriend at LOTR. I better not win this game, methinks. <br />
Deck: Gondor-Gandalf with Uruks and Moria. <br />
Good: 2 Saurons kill 4 companions<br />
Bad: She drafts Lurtz who kills my Uri with the Ring of Fury<br />
Ugly: She gets out a massive stupid swarm at site 8<br />
Result: FL shadow kill site 8<br />
0-1 <br />
Game Two<br />
Opponent: Essen PSI winner, Bas Melis who went 6-0 with knights and corsairs<br />
Deck: Gandalf ‘ Dwarf with Durin III as well! <br />
Good: Durin III’ OMG<br />
Bad: He plays like 3 Wizard Storms on me so I can never double move<br />
Ugly: At site 9, I was sure I had him but he plays not one but TWO dwarf events that make Durin defender +2. <br />
Result: FL site 9<br />
0-2 <br />
Game Three<br />
Opponent: World Cup Head judge and Reflections Draft TD, Eric Minkes<br />
Deck: 2 Balrogs! Underground sites (site 4 and 5), Rohan with Ents<br />
Good: I get to play Eric! <br />
Bad: I draw my Balrog way too early and I finally would have had a chance to play it at site 5<br />
Ugly: I got out Sauron like 4 times in this game but he dropped Filibert Bolger with Pippin at site 1 so Sauron didn’t kill as many as he should have. <br />
Result: FL site 9<br />
0-3! <br />
OMG I lost all my games! I really am like the WORST drafter ever. I better stick to Sealed and Constructed events. <br />
So, thus ends Essen. Vasco and I head back to the hotel where we engage in some mild drinking (and by mild I mean beer for him and coke for me). I then join the Decipher crew for a last supper. We try to get into the nice restaurant in the Sheraton and the head waiter suggests that our group might be better suited to eat at the bar. So we’re like, ‘‘no, we’d like to eat in the restaurant.’’ So they put a bunch of tables together in the far corner of the restaurant and give us a fixed menu of steak and fries. Scott Martins asks for a b&#39026;naise sauce for the steak to which the waiter comes back with some other basic gravy saying, ‘‘we don’t have any b&#39026;naise sauce made but this will taste good on that too.’’ Too funny. <br />
Anyway, Vasco and I head off to Dusseldorf after the meal where he gives me a driving tour of the rainy city. It’s really a beautiful town and so very old, I can’t believe it. I mean, the city was founded at the turn of the previous millennium! <br />
So, I finally get a chance to surf the net briefly before bed and see that Dom and Malboeuf and a few others from Canada had send me messages of good luck on various message boards. After that, we go to sleep (man, does that Vasco ever snore!). <br />
Day Five + 1<br />
Monday, October 25th, 2004<br />
Harry Potter is no Quiz Show <br />
So, we wake up around 8 or so and hit the closest German Macdonald’s where I try the Egg McMuffin and a cup of coffee. The breakfast sandwich is just as terrible in Germany as it is back home but the coffee is SO much better. So Vasco is kind enough to drive me to the airport and drops me off in plenty of time for my flight (which ends up being really late). <br />
I arrive in London for a 3 hour layover and hit the Irish Pub, O’Neill’s in Terminal 3 (or was it 2’) where I down 3 ciders while trying the local fish n’ chips. Not too shabby. Then again I was starving. <br />
On the Air Canada flight home, I get to watch the latest Harry Potter movie, Prisoner of Azakban or something. I have never watched nor read a Harry Potter movie or book so this was my first foray into this franchise. I wasn’t overly impressed and found it to be a pretty dark movie considering it’s for kids and everything. Afterwards Quiz Show played and I love that movie to death so I was happy I got one good movie out of the two plane rides to Europe. <br />
I arrive in Montreal around 5:30 or so in the evening. The time change is really messing with my mind so I go to see a movie with my friend, Wendy. I’ve been dying to see The Grudge starring Sarah Michelle Gellar so we go off to see that and it ends up being the single scariest movie I’ve ever seen in my entire life. So much for trying to get some sleep. If you liked The Ring even just a little bit, go see this remake of the Japanese horror flick. It’s truly terrifying. <br />
Anyway, World Cup 2004 ended up being an amazing event and I’m very happy that I went. At the beginning, the language barrier of trying to get around was pretty stressful, but in the end, I had such a great time that it was totally worth it. Hopefully more teams will make it out for next year’s foray into the very best in international competition. <br />
Props<br />
·	KwyjiboKardz.com for getting us the best cards possible for this event. That extra Radagast certainly came in handy. <br />
·	Kenneth Ellingsen for being my amazingly talented teammate both at GenCon and at World Cup. It was great playing beside you and I’m glad you love the game as much as me. <br />
·	Martin Hechtberger for holding up the team when either Kenneth or I lost our match-ups. You played really great and looked pretty snazzy in that t-shirt! For Vienna, Martin! Next year, we’ll get the trophy for sure. <br />
·	Trevor MacGregor for running a great World Cup and hosting a friendly atmosphere for all the events. <br />
·	Eric Minkes for being a great head judge for World Cup. <br />
·	Enrique Huerta for all the laughs and for introducing me to Mango ice cream. <br />
·	Mike Girard for owning me at Liar’s Dice during the last supper. <br />
·	Kyle Heuer for providing the very best memory of Essen in Dolores’ Cantina. <br />
·	Simon Schebben and Dennis Schmitz for being amazing opponents and for winning the World Cup. <br />
·	Vasco for letting me stay at his place that last night and giving me a lift to the airport as well as a tour of his hometown <br />
·	Matz Kathage for being my favourite opponent of the entire event. <br />
·	Team Rohan for being so incredibly difficult to defeat. <br />
·	Marcus Sheppard for having an 18 charisma rating <br />
·	Scott Gaeta for being worse than me at Liar’s Dice. <br />
·	Scott Martins, Toonces and Nakano for being a ton of fun all during the event, and for getting 60 new sign-up’s for LOTR Online. <br />
·	The Ice-Chucker <br />
·	Howard from Norway for all his amazing help and support during the World Cup <br />
<br />
Slops<br />
·	Irena for giving Kevin and I fake names. <br />
·	45-minute timed games in the World Cup. <br />
·	Me for forgetting my New York Yankees baseball cap on the airplane <br />
<br />
That’s it, everyone. Hope you enjoyed the read and more importantly, hope you come out to World Cup next year! <br />
